If you want to `range` over a non-rangeable thing, the idiomatic way to do this is to use an iterator approach:<p><pre><code>  var e elem
  for nonrangeable.HasNext() {
    e = nonrangeable.Next()
    // do stuff with e
  }
</code></pre>
Coincidentally, that&#x27;s what the built-in io.Copy [0] does.<p>(I&#x27;m also very biased, but I think this approach fits better with the fact that Go is targeted towards stream processing)<p>[0] <a href="http://golang.org/src/pkg/io/io.go?s=11928:11988#L330" rel="nofollow">http://golang.org/src/pkg/io/io.go?s=11928:11988#L330</a>
